==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*brōþēr'', from Indo-European ''*bʰrāter-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[brother#Old Frisian|brōther]], Old Saxon [[broþar|brōþar]] (Dutch [[broeder]]), Old High German [[bruodar]] (German [[Bruder]]), Old Norse [[bróðir]] (Swedish [[broder]]), Gothic [[𐌱𐍂𐍉𐌸𐌰𐍂]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Sanskrit [[भ्रातृ]], Avestan ''brātar-'', Ionic Greek [[φρήτωρ]], Latin [[frater|frāter]], Old Church Slavonic [[братръ]] (Russian [[брат]]), Latvian [[bralis|brãlis]], Old Irish [[bráthir]] (Welsh [[brawd]]), Tocharian A ''pracar''.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/'bɹo:ðoɹ/}}

===Noun===
'''brōþor''' ''m''
# a [[brother]]
#:''Cain gewearþ to ecg-banan angan breðer'': Cain became murderer to his own brother.  (''Beowulf'')

